passages.text: The monthly CPI indicator was surprisingly strong in July, rising \(2.8\%\) y/y against consensus and our expectations of \(2.3\%\) . While strong electricity price growth of \(13.0\%\) m/m led the headline increase, broader price pressures led to the trimmed mean accelerating to \(2.7\%\) y/y (from \(2.1\%\) y/y) and the CPI excluding volatile items rising \(3.2\%\) y/y (from \(2.5\%\) ). The monthly indicator is partial and noisy, but the component level details are consistent with our Q3 trimmed mean forecast of \(0.7\%\) q/q (due Oct 29).

The labour market was in line with expectations in July (following weakness in June), with the unemployment rate ticking down from \(4.3\%\) to \(4.2\%\) and employment increasing by \(24.5k\) . Looking through the monthly volatility, in trend terms the unemployment rate remained at \(4.2\%\) and employment increased by \(24.6k\) . Labour demand remains strong, with job ads falling \(1.0\%\) in July but flat y/y.

We expect house prices rose \(0.7\%\) m/m in August (due Sep 1) consistent with growth stabilising around a \(7\%\) annualized rate over the past few months. Housing momentum is likely to continue with prices increasing in every capital city, auction clearance rates picking up and house price expectations rising on the back of lower interest rates.

Consumer sentiment jumped \(5.7\%\) to \(98.5\) in August, its highest level in over 3 years, with gains broad- based across sub- indexes supported by a further easing in financial conditions. The household spending indicator rose \(0.5\%\) m/m and \(4.8\%\) y/y in June (slightly below expectations), while spending in May was revised slightly higher.

Business confidence (NAB measure) rose in July, while conditions eased slightly. In trend terms, confidence is at its highest level since 2H- 22 and is strongest in construction and weakest in wholesale and retail industries. Equity prices remain near record highs with risk premia around historical lows:-
